 The Federal Government has announced that it would begin the enforcement of environmental sanitation in a bid to reduce the increasing prevalence of Lassa fever across the country. This decision was taken as the latest statistics revealed that a total of 681 confirmed cases of Lassa fever had been recorded from 23 states with 132 deaths recorded since the beginning of the year. During the briefing on the update of COVID-19 pandemic response and developments, Minister of State for Health, Dr Olorunnimbe Mamora, said, “As of April 10, 2022, 4,969,571 persons have been tested for COVID-19 using the PCR or Rapid Diagnostic Test. “There has been an increase in Lagos State, decline in FCT, stability in three states – Kaduna, Kwara and Rivers, while in the other states, it has been a bit difficult to ascertain. “As of April 11, 2022, reports from the Nigeria Centre for Disease Control revealed that about 255,468 Nigerians tested positive to the virus, with 2,719 cases bing active, while 249,607 people have been treated and discharged. “Sadly, so far, we have recorded 3,142 deaths. The FG has commenced planning on scaling up sequencing by the end of April 2022. “Lassa fever confirmed cases seem to be on the rise as the present fatality rate is 19.1 per cent. There have been 3,746 suspected cases in 23 states and 681 confirmed cases with 132 deaths recorded. “Part of the government’s response to lassa fever is the enforcement of environmental sanitation and the focus on long-term improvement of water, sanitation and hygiene facilities to eliminate or reduce cholera.” The Director General of the NCDC, Dr Ifedayo Adetifa, added that “Concerning cholera, we are working behind the scenes with partners to prepare and drive the investments in water, sanitation and hygiene that are needed to prevent the kind of outbreaks that we witnessed in 2021.” 